		<div class="post" id="post-4327431">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,4327431)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-4327431">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lt-flops" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1735419); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1735419&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610205388" alt="Lt Flops" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1735419)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lt-flops" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1735419); return false;" >Lt Flops</a></span> <span class="odate time_1565494762 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">11 Aug 2019 03:39</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4327431">
									

<p>I was beginning to get intrigued by the mini Kraken story, but the fanfic-esque &quot;cryptid smut&quot; vignettes crushed my interest. As a result, I'm really not feeling this. I think if you stuck to nautical-themed cryptids, or wholesome tales related to the myth of the Kraken, the overall article would be a more enjoyable read.</p>
<p>As well, even though these are epistolary-style documents mimicking real-world forum posts, I did notice some areas where the sentence flow and tone could be improved:</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Areas&nbsp;of&nbsp;improvement</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>You had to go through a forest to find it, <strong>but it was absolutely beautiful.</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>This tells the reader that the lake is beautiful, but it neither specifies why the lake is beautiful nor attempts to evoke that beauty.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>This night, <strong>however</strong>, we noticed a small fish tank was partly buried in the sand.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I'm not sure the &quot;however&quot; (which is used to denote contrast) works in this sentence.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>which was surprising because cephalopods live in exclusively saltwater.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>A simple alteration: &quot;[&#8230;] cephalopods live exclusively in saltwater.&quot;</p>
<p>I did also notice an inconsistent use of em dashes here:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I didn't know if I did something wrong — if it didn't like the yellow color of the toy or something — I was concerned to say the least.</p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p>They swam away from the boat— resuming their playtime with the other toys like before— and I barely even noticed the sound of the rain fading.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>All em dashes in this section should be formatted the same, whereas this vignette in particular switches between two different formats &#8212; I'd stick with the first kind (space, em dash, space).</p>
<hr /></div>
</div>
</div>

